    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-08-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-08-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="645"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d645">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 (D) Regulations/367</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Oral Statement by the Japanese Ambassador</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Horinouchi</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Under Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Welles</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">August 23, 1940</hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1940-08-23">August 23, 1940</date>
                </dateline>
                <p>Concerning the embargo on the export of aviation gasoline outside the Western
                    Hemisphere, the Japanese Government attaches importance to the statement of the
                    United States Government<note n="41" xml:id="d645fn41">See statement of August
                        9, <ref target="frus1931-41v02#pg_219">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 219</ref>.</note> that the measure,
                    which virtually accords preferential treatment to the nations of the Americas,
                    is necessary in the interest of national defense. The Japanese Government
                    maintains its views expressed in the Japanese Ambassador’s note of August 3,
                        1940,<note n="42" xml:id="d645fn42">
                        <ref target="frus1931-41v02#pg_218">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, p. 218</ref>.</note> and will observe with
                    keen interest the actual application of the export restrictions.</p>
            </div>
